<subSubSection pageId="25" pageNumber="586" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="25.[130,777,1138,1374]" pageId="25" pageNumber="586">DIAGNOSIS. — Colonies branched, with well defined axial stem and alternate secondary and tertiary branches. Sinuous or straight longitudinal ridges separating apertural rows often present. Axial region formed by well defined linear axis. Autozooecia attenuated to weakly inflated at their bases, having subtriangular cross-section in endozone, becoming elliptical in exozone, orientated at angles of 30-90° to colony surface. Diaphragms rare to absent. Exozonal wall material well developed, with narrow zooecial boundaries. Metazooecia absent.Paurostyles scattered to common, usually developed on ridges.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="25" pageNumber="586" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="25.[132,775,1397,1447]" pageId="25" pageNumber="586">OCCURRENCE. — Middle to Upper Ordovician; North America, Europe.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
